With no access to the gym during the pandemic, I challenged myself to transform my full body by working out at a playground for 30 days. No weights. Just gravity and callisthenics. I hope I made Chris Heria proud!

DIET
I practiced intermittent fasting in the morning and ate a large lunch and dinner at around 2pm and 9pm, respectively. I followed my usual diet during this challenge, which consists of mostly Chinese food (a mix of meat, vegetables and rice or noodles). I personally think that I should have eaten more during this challenge in order to gain more mass. I drank protein powder for the first week, then I ran out lol.

FULL-BODY WORKOUT ROUTINE

Monday, Wednesday, Friday:
Abs:
- Reverse Crunch x 20 reps x 3 sets
Back:
- Pull-up x 10 reps x 3 sets
- Inverted Rows x 10 reps x 3 sets
Biceps:
- Chin-up x 10 reps x 3 sets
- Monkey Bar Chin-ups x 10 reps x 3 sets
Legs:
- Single-Leg Calf Raises x 10 reps x 3 sets x 2 legs
- Platform Jump x 10 reps x 3 sets

Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday:
Abs:
- Hanging Knee Tucks x 20 reps x 3 sets
Legs:
- Elevated Back Lunge x 10 reps x 3 sets x 2 legs
Chest:
- Push-up or Decline Push-up x MAX reps x 3 sets
- Spiderman or Archer Push-up x MAX reps x 3 sets
Triceps:
- Dip x 10 reps x 3 sets
- Straight Bar Dip x 10 reps x 3 sets

- Platform Jump x 10 reps x 3 sets

Rest Day

So you're stuck at home, and your hair is getting a bit too long. Today, I'm going to teach you how to give yourself an easy haircut, step by step, with a method designed for beginners. Specifically, a faded undercut for men with straight or Asian hair. This is also a good tutorial on how to cut your husband or boyfriend's hair.

I'm not a professional! This is my own self cut system, and this is just what works for me.

Yes, this video is the video from the YouTube Premium ad.

----

POPULAR QUESTION: What are the mm sizes you used in guard numbers?

The guards I used were #1 (3mm), #2 (6mm), and #3 (9mm)
My taper control switch went, from position 1 to 5: 0.8mm, 1.1mm, 1.4mm, 1.7mm, 2.0mm

It'll depend on your clipper, but essentially, you just need to add the measurements together to try to match my sizes.

So for example, when I was cutting at 3.8mm, I was using a #1 guard + position 1 (3mm + 0.8mm = 3.8mm)
When I was cutting at 5mm, I was using a #1 guard + position 5 (3mm + 2.0mm = 5mm)

As long as you understand the process of going from a smaller size to a longer size and cutting in layers, you should be good! If you're around the measurements I used, you should get something similar to my haircut.

In this video, I tried selling AI Art , or artwork created by artificial intelligence, by creating an AI Art business on platforms such as Fiverr and Facebook. I try out generators like Stable Diffusion, DALLE 2, Midjourney, and NightCafe. It was a wild adventure filled with surprises and drama!

HOW TO GENERATE AI ART FOR BEGINNERS:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Browse Lexica: https://lexica.art/

To get good at generating AI art, you need to first understand how prompts work. A prompt is what you tell the AI art generator to generate. Lexica is a site like Google that shows AI art and the prompts used to generate them. Super useful to find prompts you can use when generating yourself.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Use NightCafe: https://creator.nightcafe.studio/?code=JENSEN

You can generate AI Art using NightCafe. They offer 5 free credits every day that you can claim. You can buy credits if you run out, or just wait until the next day to claim more.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Install and use Stable Diffusion: https://youtu.be/pA-njBq1qmM

Installing and running Stable Diffusion on your own computer will give you the most customization and power when generating AI art. You can generate unlimited images, utilize custom models, and features such as Initial Image (img2img).

Running a local version requires a computer with a powerful NVIDIA GPU. If you don't have an NVIDIA GPU, you can still run it with your CPU, but it will be very slow (as shown in my video). 

The easiest way to install and use Stable Diffusion is with cmdr2's version. Watch this video (https://youtu.be/pA-njBq1qmM) to learn how to do it. Also, leave a comment and say that Jensen sent you! The video tutorial is really underrated!

Shoutout to Corridor Digital for introducing me to AI Art. Their video on it is a great watch (and also introduces Dreambooth, which is feature I didn't get into in my video): https://youtu.be/W4Mcuh38wyM

Another shoutout to Gilbatree for sharing his experience selling AI Art on Fiverr. It was useful during this challenge. I copied some of his Fiverr gig titles word for word. Check out his video: https://youtu.be/9nTJJGyPjbI

DIET
I practiced intermittent fasting in the morning and ate a large lunch and dinner at around 2pm and 9pm, respectively. I followed my usual diet during this challenge, which consists of mostly Chinese food (a mix of meat, vegetables and rice or noodles). I ate more salads than usual. I also drank smoothies mixed with Ritual protein.

FULL-BODY WORKOUT ROUTINE

Monday, Wednesday, Friday:
Abs:
- Reverse Crunch x 25 reps x 2 sets
Back:
- Pull-up x 10 reps x 3 sets
- Barbell Row (with log or rock) x 10 reps x 3 sets
Biceps:
- Chin-up x 10 reps x 3 sets
- Bicep Curl (with log or rock) x 10 reps x 3 sets

Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday:
Abs:
- Hanging Knee Tucks x 25 reps x 2 sets

Rest Day

In this video, I break down how much YouTube has paid me for 12 million views, which I've collected over 4 self-haircut videos.

GOOGLE ADSENSE
For those who don't know, Google Adsense is YouTube's advertising program. Every time you see an ad on a YouTube video, YouTube pays the creator of that video, assuming they meet the requirements of the YouTube Partnership Program, a certain amount of ad revenue. Generally speaking, the more views a video gets, the more chances ads can be shown, and the more ad revenue the creator of the video earns. 

Bringing together my 4 self-haircut videos, I earned a total of $7,755.42 in ad revenue.

LICENSING FEES
YouTube reached out to me to license my self-haircut tutorial video, which is basically getting permission from me to use it.

There are contracts in place so I can't share with you what YouTube paid me, but what I can share is that my standard licensing fee is in the 4 digits.

BRAND SPONSORSHIPS
Out of my 4 self-haircut videos, one of them had a brand sponsorship integration from Skillshare.

Again, I can't disclose the exact amount that I earned because of contracts, but I can say that my standard brand sponsorship fee is in the 4 digits.

AFFILIATE MARKETING
Affiliate marketing involves referring a product or service, and being paid a commission every time a purchase or sign-up is generated from your referral. On YouTube, you often see this as affiliate links in the description of YouTube videos, where if you use that link, the YouTube creator earns a commission from it.

Taking a look at my Amazon Associates account, I have earned $3,859.77.

NFT
NFT, or Non-Fungible Token, are the talk of the town in the crypto world right now, and are a cryptographic token that represents something unique. It is essentially a one-of-a-kind, digital collectible. Just like there are unique physical assets, like the Mona Lisa, NFTs are unique digital assets, like a digital photo of Nyan Cat, or a digital video from the artist Beeple, that can be authenticated by the blockchain.

TIKTOK
Although I haven't earned money from my self-haircut video on TikTok, I give sole credit to the video for kickstarting my TikTok, and now, TikTok is another revenue stream for my brand.

I wanted to bring this up because sometimes, revenue comes in the form of opportunities. Opportunities that you can act on to generate revenue.
